'''Sir Dallas Gerald Mercer Bernard, 1st Baronet''' (22 March 1888 – 26 November 1975) was a banker in England, Hong Kong, and in Middle East.

== Early life ==
Bernard was born on 22 March 1888. Bernards's parents were Edmund Bowen Bernard and Arabella Margaret Piercy.
Bernard studied at [[Stubbington House School]] in [[Fareham]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]]. 

== Education ==
After Bernard held the rank of midshipman in the [[Royal Navy]], he attended [[Thames Nautical Training College]] in [[Foots Cray Place]], [[Kent]].<ref name="Peerage">{{cite web|work=The Peerage|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p13970.htm#c139696.1|title=Sir Dallas Gerald Mercer Bernard, 1st Bt.|accessdate=7 December 2013}}</ref>

== Career ==
Bernard arrived in the Far East and joined [[Jardine Matheson|Jardine, Matheson & Co.]] by at least 1912, at which point he was working there as an assistant.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Directory & Chronicle for China, Japan, Corea, Indo-China, Straits Settlements, Malay States, Siam, Netherlands India, Borneo, the Philippines, &c. |date=1912 |publisher=Hong Kong Daily Press Office |pages=1111–1112 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4tEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1111 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |chapter=Foreign Residents}}</ref> He was chairman of the trustees of the Sailors' Home and on the Local General Committee of the Missions to Seamen in Hong Kong in the 1920s.<ref name="Strong to Save">{{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Stephen |title=Strong to Save |date=19 July 2017 |publisher=City U Press |location=Hong Kong |isbn=962937305X |page =142 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mB4wDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA142 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |chapter=Headwinds and Adverse Currents |quote= [Bishop Duppuy] had already discussed the matter with a fellow Mission Local General Committee member and the chairman of the Sailors' Home trustees, D.G.M. Bernard of Jardine Matheson & Co. . . . }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Davies |first1=Stephen |title=Strong to Save |date=19 July 2017 |publisher=City U Press |location=Hong Kong |isbn=962937305X |page = 494 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mB4wDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA494 |accessdate=16 August 2018 |quote= At this point [late 1922 or early 1923] the Local Committee comprised . . . D.G.M. Bernard Esq (Jardine Matheson) . . . }}</ref> He was the managing director of Jardine Matheson from 1928 to 1942.  Bernard was also director of other companies such as the Chinese Central Railways between 1928 and 1942 and the [[RSA Insurance Group|Alliance Assurance Company]] between 1931 and 1942.<ref name="Peerage"/> Bernard was also the chairman of the [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Reading Eagle|date=12 December 1948|title=Governor of Bank of England Is Youngest in 101 Years|page=36|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19481212&id=mqEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LJoFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3968,4983069}}</ref> During his time in Hong Kong he was appointed [[Unofficial Member|unofficial member]] of the [[Executive Council of Hong Kong|Executive Council]] in 1926 and 1927 and [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] in 1926. He was on the Legislative Council's Standing Law Committee.<ref>{{cite web |title=Minutes February 23rd, 1928 |url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/1928/h280223.pdf |publisher=Legislative Council of Hong Kong |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>

Bernard became the director of the Bank of England from 1936 to 1949 and the [[High Sheriff of the County of London]] from 1942 to 1943 and later on the Lieutenant of the City of London. After the war, he continued to serve the bank and rose to the deputy-governor of the Bank of England in 1949 until in 1954 when he left the bank.<ref name="Peerage"/>

After leaving the Bank of England, Bernard joined the [[Courtaulds]] and became the director between 1954 and 1956 and between 1964 and 1965 and also the deputy-chairman from 1956 to 1962. He was also active in banking in the Middle East. In 1954, he was appointed chairman of the Jordan Currency Board, which became the sole authority entitled to issue [[Jordanian dinar]]. He held the post until 1957 and continued as the chairman of the [[British Bank of the Middle East]] from 1954 until 1965.<ref name="Peerage"/>

He was created [[Bernard baronets|1st Baronet Bernard]], of Snakemoor, in the [[County of Southampton]] on 27 January 1954.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=40097 |date=9 February 1954 |page=865}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Bernard married Betty Addis, daughter of Sir Charles Stewart Addis and Elizabeth Jane McIsaac on 16 November 1922. Bernard died on 26 November 1975 at age 87. Bernard and his wife have three children: <ref name="Peerage"/>
Elizabeth Piercy Bernard (10 April 1924 – 29 November 1981), Sir Dallas Bernard, 2nd Bt. (born 14 Dec 1926), and Margaret Anne Bernard (6 June 1929 – 7 Oct 2010).

