'''Josep Pintat-Solans''' (January 21, 1925<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=92bJlWbPeKMC&q=Josep+Pintat-Solans+Jan.+21,+1925&dq=Josep+Pintat-Solans+Jan.+21,+1925&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYmN7MxLHdAhUD6IMKHZszCvMQ6AEIJzAA|title=Who'S Who in the World: 199l-1992|last=who|first=Marguis Who's|date=1990|publisher=Marquis Who's Who|isbn=9780837911106|language=en}}</ref><ref name="worldstatesmen">{{cite web |last=Cahoon |first=Ben |title=Andorra |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Andorra.html |work=WorldStatesmen.org |date=2000 |accessdate=2008-12-01}}</ref> &ndash; October 20, 2007<ref name="embassy">{{cite web |title=News |url=http://www.andorra.be/en/index.htm |publisher=Embassy of the Principality of Andorra in Belgium |accessdate=2008-12-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701190504/http://www.andorra.be/en/index.htm |archivedate=2010-07-01 |df= }}</ref>) was the second [[List of heads of government of Andorra|Prime Minister of Andorra]].  A local [[business executive]], he was unanimously elected Prime Minister by the [[General Council of Andorra]] and began serving on May 21, 1984;<ref name="worldstatesmen" /><ref name="europa">{{cite book |last=Maher |first=Joanne |title=The Europa World Year Book 2004 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MdXLYfoJZ0kC |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2004 |accessdate=2008-12-01 |isbn=1-85743-254-1 |page=486}}</ref> Pintat-Solans was re-elected in January 1986, receiving the votes of 27 out of 28 of the General Council's members, serving as Prime Minister until January 12, 1990.<ref name="worldstatesmen" /><ref name="europa" />  He died on October 20, 2007, after a long illness.<ref name="embassy" />

