{{Infobox person | name = Lavoslav Singer | image = Industrialist Lavoslav Singer.jpg | imagesize = 200px | birth_date = 1866 | birth_place = [[Bulinac]], near [[Bjelovar]], [[Austrian Empire]], (now [[Croatia]]) | death_date = 1942 (aged 76) | death_place = [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] | death_cause = Murdered in [[Holocaust]] | relations = | spouse = Amalia ([[Married and maiden names|née]] Herenshtein) Singer | children = | nationality = [[Croats|Croat]] | other_names = | occupation = [[Business magnate|Industrialist]] | known_for = }}
'''Lavoslav Singer''' (1866&ndash;1942) was [[Croatia]]n industrialist notable for his role in the development of [[Bjelovar]].
Singer was born in village [[Bulinac]] (part of [[Nova Rača]]), into a Croatian [[Jews|Jewish]] family of Josip (Yosef) Singer. He was educated at the best business schools in [[Austrian Empire]]. Upon completion of his education he was engaged in industrial revolution that led to the development of factories in Bjelovar. Singer developed the milling industry in Bjelovar, but was also active in the development of coal mining, gravel extraction from the river [[Drava]] and its shipment to the big cities, and has also extracted gold from Drava. Singer was one of the leading [[financier]]s and representative of [[Concession (contract)|concessionaires]] that built the railway Bjelovar-[[Garešnica]]/[[Grubišno Polje]]. He was one of the most important and wealthiest townsman of Bjelovar.<ref>{{harvtxt|Miodrag Savkovitch|1926|p=168}}</ref><ref>{{hr icon}} Mira Kolar-Dimitrijević: ''Pretvaranje Bjelovara iz vojničkoga u privredno središte od 1871. do 1910. godine.'': stranica 44: Bjelovar: 16 svibanj 2007.</ref><ref>{{hr icon}} Podravina: Željko Karaula - Mira Kolar-Dimitrijević: ''Studije iz povijesti Bjelovara (1848.-1991).'': Volumen 10: broj 20: stranica 174: Koprivnica: 2011.</ref><ref>{{hr icon}} Ruah Hadaša (Glasilo Židovske vjerske zajednice Bet Israel): Željko Karaula: ''Holokaust u Bjelovaru - nestanak Židovske zajednice u Bjelovaru tijekom razdoblja NDH'': stranica 27, broj 11, godina IV, 2009.</ref> Singer was married to Amalia ([[Married and maiden names|née]] Herenshtein) Singer. As a Jews, during [[World War II]], Singer and his wife were forced to wear [[Yellow badge|yellow star of David]] on their clothes.<ref>{{hr icon}} Hrvatski državni arhiv; Mirjana Jurić; ''Analitički inventar, Ravnateljstvo ustaškog redarstva – Židovski odsjek 1941-1942''; stranica 18; 2005.</ref> In 1942 Singer and his wife were arrested and deported to [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] where they were killed during the [[Holocaust]]. He was 76 years old.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://db.yadvashem.org/names/nameDetails.html?itemId=1660696&language=en|title=Lavoslav Singer|publisher=[[Yad Vashem]]|work=Pages of testimony by Yaakov Harel (relative)}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://db.yadvashem.org/names/nameDetails.html?itemId=1545817&language=en|title=Amalya Singer|publisher=[[Yad Vashem]]|work=Pages of testimony by Yaakov Harel (relative)}}</ref>
