{{Japanese name|Mieno}}
{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Yasushi Mieno |native_name = {{nobold|三重野 康}} |image = |caption = |office = 26th [[Bank of Japan|Governor of the Bank of Japan]] |term_start = 17 December 1989 |term_end = 16 December 1994 |predecessor = [[Satoshi Sumita]] |successor = [[Yasuo Matsushita]] |birth_date = {{birth date|1924|3|17}} |birth_place = [[Ōita Prefecture|Ōita]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] |death_date = {{death date and age|2012|4|15|1924|3|17}} |death_place = |alma_mater = [[University of Tokyo|Tokyo Imperial University]] }}
<!-- [[File:___.jpg|thumb|right|Yasushi Mieno]] --> {{nihongo|'''Yasushi Mieno'''|三重 野康|Mieno Yasushi|March 17, 1924 &ndash; April 15, 2012}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] businessman, central banker, the 26th Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ) and a Director of the [[Bank for International Settlements]] (BIS).<ref name="seligman">Siegman, Charles J. [http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+Bank+for+International+Settlements+and+the+Federal+Reserve.-a015850047 "The Bank for International Settlements and the Federal Reserve,"] ''Federal Reserve Bulletin.'' October 1, 1994.</ref><ref name="Bloomberg obituary">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2012-04-18/mieno-governor-who-pricked-japan-s-bubble-economy-dies-at-88|title=Mieno, Governor Who Pricked Japan's Bubble Economy, Dies|last=Mayumi Otsuma|date=April 18, 2012|publisher=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=18 April 2012}}</ref>
==Early life== Mieno was born in [[Ōita, Ōita|Ōita]].<ref>Bank of Japan (BOJ), [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/sousai26.htm/ 26th Governor]</ref>
==Career== From April 1975 through February 1978, Mieno was head of the BOJ banking department.<ref name="werner147">Werner, Richard A. (2003). {{Google books|bHLC7VOc9JoC|''Princes of the Yen: Japan's Central Bankers and the Transformation of the Economy,'' p. 147|page=147}}</ref>
Mieno was BOJ Governor from December 17, 1989 to December 16, 1994,<ref>BOJ, [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/index.htm/ List of Governors]</ref> having previously served as Deputy Governor from 1984 to 1989.<ref name="werner147"/>
In 1994, he was an elected member of the BIS Board of Directors.<ref name="seligman"/>
On April 15, 2012, Mieno died from [[heart failure]] in a Tokyo hospital.<ref name="Bloomberg obituary"/>
==Selected works== In a statistical overview derived from writings by and about Yasushi Mieno, [[OCLC]]/[[WorldCat]] encompasses roughly 7 works in 10 publications in 2 languages and 50+ library holdings.<ref>[http://www.oclc.org/research/activities/identities/default.htm WorldCat Identities]: [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-nr94-1247 Mieno, Yasushi 1924- &nbsp;]</ref> {{dynamic list}} * ''World Economy in the 1990s: a Japanese Central Banker's View'' (1990) * ''Current Monetary and Economic Conditions in Japan'' (1993) * 日本経済と中央銀行: 前日銀総裁講演錄 by 三重野康 (1995) * 利を見て義を思う: 三重野康の金融政策講義 (2000)
